f Congress Web site as a raster image. Vault AACR2: 100; 651/1; 710/1"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-04-29T15:39:57.538Z", "group": ["gmd.mar", "catalog-split-15", "catalog", "general-maps", "main-catalog-split-15"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/73693388/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002020.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002020.gif#h=150&w=193", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002020/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=856&w=1102", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002020/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=1712&w=2204"], "index": 20, "language": ["english"], "location": ["south bend", "united states", "indiana"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/tiff", "image/jpeg", "image/jp2"], "number": ["2005-01-06t08:17:09", "73693388", "2025-06-07t18:29:47.900000"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["map"], "partof": ["panoramic maps", "geography and map division", "catalog", "cities and towns"], "score": 33.453007, "shelf_id": "G4094.S6A3 1866 .R8", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["south bend (ind.)", "aerial views", "indiana", "united states", "south bend"], "timestamp": "2026-04-29T16:12:28.837Z", "title": "South Bend, Indiana 1866", "type": ["cartographic"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/73693388/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/73693389", "http://www.loc.gov/item/73693389/", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/f58f7fcb-3a4b-5d2c-8740-eb7284aff219", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g4094s.pm002030", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/g4094s.pm002030/"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["ruger, a.", "stoner, j. j.", "chicago lithographing co", "charles shober & co"], "date": "1874", "dates": ["1874"], "description": ["\"This panoramic map shows South Bend, Indiana, as it appeared in 1874. The map shows the town on both sides of the Saint Joseph River, connected by rail and foot bridges. In the right foreground, a train enters the view on the tracks of the Michigan Central Iles Branch. Another train has just crossed the river on the tracks of the Chicago and Lake Huron Railroad, and in the right background, a train is shown traveling on the Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railroad. The numbered and lettered key at the bottom of the map indicates the main sites of interest in the town, which include the court house, county jail, schools, post office, water works, gas works, railroad depots, hotels, various manufactories, and numerous houses of worship, including Catholic, Baptist, Christian, Episcopal, Evangelical, Lutheran, Methodist, Presbyterian, and Universalist. The large factory complex located near the tracks of the Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railroad between Lafayette Street and Prairie Avenue housed the Studebaker Brothers Wagon Manufactory. Founded in 1852, the Studebaker company became a leader in the manufacture of horse-drawn carriages, and later, of automobiles. South Bend was originally settled as a fur trading post. The town was incorporated in 1835 and grew into an industrial powerhouse during the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. The panoramic map was a cartographic form popularly used to depict U.S. and Canadian cities and towns in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Also known as bird's-eye views or perspective maps, these maps are representations of cities portrayed as if viewed from above at an oblique angle. Not generally drawn to scale, they show street patterns, individual buildings, and major landscape features in perspective. This map is by Albert Ruger (1829-99), the first American to achieve success as a panoramic artist. Born in Prussia, Ruger immigrated to the United States and worked initially as a mason. While serving with the Ohio Volunteers during the Civil War, he drew views of Union campsites. After the war, Ruger settled in Battle Creek, Michigan, where he began his panoramic mapping career by sketching Michigan cities. In the late 1860s, Ruger formed a partnership with J.J. Stoner of Madison, Wisconsin, and together they published numerous city panoramas.\" World Digital Library."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-04-29T15:39:56.921Z", "group": ["gmd.mar", "catalog-split-00", "catalog", "general-maps", "main-catalog-split-00"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/73693389/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002030.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002030.gif#h=150&w=183", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002030/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=838&w=1024", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002030/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=1676&w=2048"], "index": 21, "language": ["english"], "location": ["south bend", "united states", "indiana"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/tiff", "image/jpeg", "image/jp2"], "number": ["2022-07-14t10:56:31", "73693389", "2025-06-07t18:29:48.200000"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["map"], "partof": ["catalog", "panoramic maps", "cities and towns", "world digital library", "geography and map division"], "score": 33.453007, "shelf_id": "G4094.S6A3 1874 .R8", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["south bend (ind.)", "aerial views", "indiana", "united states", "south bend"], "timestamp": "2026-04-29T16:12:28.837Z", "title": "South Bend, Indiana 1874", "type": ["cartographic"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/73693389/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/75693227", "http://www.loc.gov/item/75693227/", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/ab338757-ebcd-5244-b5a2-03ee40182f4b", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g4094s.pm002040", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/g4094s.pm002040/"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["pauli, c. j."], "date": "1890", "dates": ["1890"], "description": ["Bird's-eye view. \"Looking west.\" Includes illus. and index to points of interest. Perspective map not drawn to scale. LC Panoramic maps (2nd ed.), 204 Available also through the Library of Congress Web site as a raster image. AACR2"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-04-29T15:40:09.007Z", "group": ["gmd.mar", "catalog-split-09", "catalog", "general-maps", "main-catalog-split-09"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/75693227/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002040.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd409/g4094/g4094s/pm002040.gif#h=150&w=219", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002040/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=1088&w=1588", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd409:g4094:g4094s:pm002040/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=2176&w=3176"], "index": 22, "language": ["english"], "location": ["south bend", "united states", "indiana"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/tiff", "image/jpeg", "image/jp2"], "number": ["2002-12-14t18:40:04", "75693227", "2025-06-07t18:30:52"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["map"], "partof": ["panoramic maps", "geography and map division", "catalog", "cities and towns"], "score": 33.453007, "shelf_id": "G4094.S6A3 1890 .P3", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["south bend (ind.)", "aerial views", "indiana", "united states", "south bend"], "timestamp": "2026-04-29T16:15:55.865Z", "title": "South Bend, Ind. 1890", "type": ["cartographic"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/75693227/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/2019629578", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2019629578/", "https://www.recordedbooks.com/title-details/9781684419319", "http://d2cv0ie6dlin9h.cloudfront.net/DD43477/DD43477_image_148x230.jpg"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["buttigieg, pete"], "date": "2019", "dates": ["2019"], "description": ["A mayor's inspirational story of a Midwest city that has become nothing less than a blueprint for the future of American renewal. Once described by the Washington Post as \"the most interesting mayor you've never heard of,\" Pete Buttigieg, the thirty-six-year-old Democratic mayor of South Bend, Indiana, has improbably emerged as one of the nation's most visionary politicians. First elected in 2011, Buttigieg left a successful business career to move back to his hometown, previously tagged by Newsweek as a 'dying city,' because the industrial Midwest beckoned as a challenge to the McKinsey-trained Harvard graduate. While Washington reels with scandal, this audiobook interweaves two once-unthinkable success stories: that of an Afghanistan veteran who came out and found love and acceptance, all while in office, and that of a Rust Belt city so thoroughly transformed that it shatters the way we view America's so-called flyover country."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2023-10-27T08:59:14.937Z", "group": ["catalog-split-01", "catalog", "main-catalog-split-01"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://lccn.loc.gov/2019629578", "image_url": [], "index": 23, "language": ["english"], "location": ["south bend", "indiana"], "number": ["audio disc", "2019629578", "n1090766045", "2023-10-25t10:03:46"], "original_format": ["sound recording"], "other_title": ["One mayor's challenge and a model for America's future"], "partof": ["catalog"], "score": 29.871647, "shelf_id": "RZC 6907", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["political science / american government / local", "south bend (ind.)", "autobiographies", "afghan war", "mayors", "veterans", "gay politicians", "politics and government", "urban renewal", "gay men", "biographies", "biography", "south bend", "audiobooks", "buttigieg, pete", "indiana"], "timestamp": "2023-10-27T09:00:40.841Z", "title": "Shortest way home : one mayor's challenge and a model for America's future", "type": ["sound recording-n